    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      The Ferny Grove rail line is a genuine commuter asset for Keperra residents. The station provides direct connections to the CBD, and for families where one or both partners work in the city, that daily time saving is factored into suburb selection. The Blackwood Street dining and retail precinct in adjacent Mitchelton is readily accessible, giving Keperra residents practical everyday amenity without requiring them to travel further. For the family buyer who has been weighing the northern corridor options seriously, Keperra represents the point where more land and quieter streets become available while maintaining the rail access and broader corridor amenity they have been prioritising.
    </p>
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      The housing stock in Keperra includes a range of post-war brick homes, weatherboard houses, and an increasing number of renovated properties that reflect the suburb's appeal to buyers who want space and potential at a northern Brisbane address. The generous block sizes are the defining feature for most buyers: backyard space, the possibility of a pool, the scope for a granny flat or extension, and simply the outdoor lifestyle that larger land provides. Sellers who understand this and present their outdoor spaces as the asset they are consistently attract stronger buyer interest than comparable properties that downplay the land.
    </p>
    <div style="display:flex; gap:1.5rem; flex-wrap:wrap;">
